steps.description:
It's important to be aware that Sweet Shrub lasts a long time and can be quite invasive. As a result, you may prefer it in a large garden as it may spread too wide if you only have a smaller patch. Sweet Shrub is a prolific seed producer but the plant tends to spread by putting out suckers that root themselves. You may want to be vigilant about that if you want to control the plant in your own garden. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/b/be/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Also take care that it doesn't invade your neighbors! Pinch out suckers in the spring to contain the plant’s spread. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/2b/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sweet Shrub isn't fussy about the kind of soil it grows in, but it will do best in a moist, rich soil with plenty of room for growth. Avoid boggy locations or anywhere puddles tend to linger after rainfall. The plant won’t mind a clay soil. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/a/ab/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sweet shrub also has a slight preference for neutral or slightly acid soil. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/c/c7/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sweet Shrub can easily be grown from seeds. Simply sow the seeds in springtime (March or April), preferably in a shady area of the garden in rich, well-drained, loamy soil. Some gardeners are unlucky enough to chance upon an unscented variety when growing from seed. To prevent this, you can try planting more seeds than you need plants and removing any that emerge unscented when the plants eventually flower. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/15/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/1/15/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

It will take two or three years for a plant grown from seed to flower. Flowers first appear in mid-March and continue into May. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a4/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/a/a4/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you are buying a nursery plant, try to buy it while it is blooming to get an idea of the fragrance. Plant in loamy soil, in shade conditions. Alternately you can buy a named cultivar that is known for having a good fragrance. 'Michael Lindsey' is known for having a pleasant fragrance as well as attractive shiny leaves. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/92/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/9/92/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Avoid taking plants from the wild as these are endangered in some areas. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/fa/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/f/fa/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sweet Shrub requires little in the way of maintenance, but you may like to prune it to keep the plant in shape and prevent it from growing too wide. Pruning should be done immediately after flowering, which means in the early summer. Due to the fact that this plant spreads by producing side shoots known as suckers, you can control the width by pinching these off as they emerge. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9e/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/9/9e/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Thinning out old growth will usually ensure the new growth comes through more vigorously the following growing season. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/26/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/26/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sweet Shrub doesn’t tend to be bothered by disease but root rot can occur in poorly-drained soil. To avoid this, don’t plant the bush where puddles form and don’t easily drain away. If you observe warty growths on stems close to the ground, this may indicate bacterial crown gall. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f5/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/f/f5/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The best solution is to remove the plant and surrounding soil to prevent re-infection. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9f/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/9/9f/Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/aid4863831-v4-728px-Plant-a-Sweet-Shrub-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
